        {
            "id": "b1eef76ad4f34c9b9b962",
            "questionText": "A cyclist pedals up a hill with a constant speed. The hill has a height of $!$50\\text{ m}$!$ and the cyclist and bicycle have a combined weight of $!$700\\text{ N}$!$. The cyclist's power output is $!$100\\text{ W}$!$ and they take $!$60\\text{ s}$!$ to reach the top. The cyclist's body consumes $!$8000\\text{ J}$!$ of energy during that time. Determine the efficiency of the cyclist's energy conversion during the ascent.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "9f45ddc08854436b941ab",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the relationship between power, time, and work done. Which formula correctly relates work done ($!$W$!$) to constant power ($!$P$!$) and time ($!$t$!$)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2691d473-fa9f-48af-866f-fcf735cf65ac"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$W = P t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$W = P + t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$W = P t^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "51e45b3b0702410dae4e0",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, use the chosen relationship with the given values ($!$P=100\\text{ W}$!$ and $!$t=60\\text{ s}$!$) to calculate the total mechanical work output. Compute $!$W = P \\times t$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "6000"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2691d473-fa9f-48af-866f-fcf735cf65ac"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "05f96addc265451b8425b",
                    "stepText": "Now, let's identify the concept needed to calculate efficiency. Which formula correctly represents the efficiency ($!$\\eta$!$) as the ratio of useful work output to energy consumed?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0be92c40-ded4-48ee-a466-07236da03b9f"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta = \\frac{\\text{useful energy out}}{\\text{actual energy in}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta = \\frac{\\text{actual energy in}}{\\text{useful energy out}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta = \\text{useful energy out} \\times \\text{actual energy in}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "0ec8e70686da4446a556b",
                    "stepText": "Using the work output computed earlier and the energy consumed by the cyclist's body (given as $!$8000\\text{ J}$!$), apply the efficiency formula to calculate the efficiency of energy conversion.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
